&lt;br /&gt;
That seems to be Vyasa's only mission, because after the story, he leaves. &amp;nbsp;Soon after, King Jayadratha of Sindh passes by the camp while the brothers are away hunting. &amp;nbsp;He spots Draupadi alone and undefended, so he grabs her and runs off.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The brothers quickly get wind of this and pursue him through the jungle. &amp;nbsp;The princess is retrieved and Jayadratha's followers decimated, but the king himself has his life spared because he happens to be a kinsman of theirs-- he is Ghandari's nephew.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Jayadratha is not nearly so forgiving as the Pandavas, and he seeks revenge for the humiliation he suffered during his captivity at the hands of Bhimasena. &amp;nbsp;He lives in the wilderness, worshipping Shiva until the god offers him a boon. &amp;nbsp;After some negotiation, they settle on granting him the ability to stay the brothers during a cavalry attack, except for Arjun, whom even gods have a hard time stopping!&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="blogger-post-footer"&gt;&lt;img width='1' height='1' src='https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/tracker/5100791158359408086-5236571148576816817?l=mahabharatapodcast.blogspot.com' alt='' /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class="feedflare"&gt;
